\f0 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 The context\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec4 Since the last consultation cycle, a deepening energy crisis and a litany of Conservative policy failures\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 means the UK is facing a bleak economic outlook.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The cost of living crisis also continues unabated with 2023 looking set to be a dire one for living standards as\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 the price of energy and other essentials is expected to stay elevated. Meanwhile, higher interest rates are\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 feeding through into higher borrowing costs for families and businesses, while homeowners face steep rises\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 in monthly mortgage payments.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 A series of Conservative economic policy failures have left us uniquely exposed to this crisis, including\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 decisions to wind down gas storage capacity, failure to insulate our ageing housing stock, dither and delay\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 on nuclear and e\uc0\u64256 ective bans on cheap renewable energy like onshore wind.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 This year\'92s consultation cycle has been framed around the \'91everyday economy\'92 which is those parts of the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 economy which keep\'a0our country moving and\'a0society functioning. It is made up of the private and public\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 sectors and includes health, social care, retail, utilities, transport, post, child care, construction, education\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 and food.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The everyday economy has been overlooked and undervalued by the Conservatives and this has weakened\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 our country\'92s foundations. Neglect of areas that support the everyday economy, such as skills and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 enforcement, has led to low pay, low productivity and inadequate progression.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The pandemic showed the importance of key workers and yet still too many jobs are low paid, insecure and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 the Government has no strategy to address this.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 While policymakers are rightly concerned with the immediate energy crisis, the long-term outlook for growth\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 and prosperity, in the everyday economy and beyond, remains grim.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 13 years of stagnation and low growth has left our economy wholly unprepared and lacking in resilience. It is\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 no surprise the International Monetary Fund expects the UK to have the lowest growth and lowest in\uc0\u64258 ation of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 any major advanced economy over the next two years.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The Government has no real plan for growth and has already caved to their own backbenchers on key\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 measures around housebuilding and renewable energy.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The Prime Minister has no vision for capitalising on the opportunities around net zero and seems content to let\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 potential jobs, investment and growth slip away to other countries.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The Government also look set to repeat the failures of the past decade, where some welcome progress in\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 renewable generation has failed to deliver jobs in the UK because of avoidable policy mistakes.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The Conservatives continue to ask working people to foot the bill for their economic failures \'96 picking their\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 pockets \uc0\u64257 rst with huge tax hikes, while the mega-rich and energy giants enjoy untargeted tax breaks.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 After 13 years of Conservative government our public services are in crisis with many increasingly struggling\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 to provide the service expected of them and meet demand. There are growing recruitment and retention\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 crises among many workforces and the government has repeatedly failed to address this, which has directly\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 contributed to industrial action.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The Conservatives have sought to sow division and stoke political \uc0\u64257 ghts instead of trying to \u64257 nd solutions,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 proposing new unworkable and unfair restrictions on trade union activity that threaten to further undermine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 workers\'92 rights and living standards instead of negotiating and resolving issues.\cf0 \cb1 \
